    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>A Republican Plan For Health Care</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter by Speaker J Dennis Hastert replies to Oct 14 editorial criticizing measure to allow the uninsured to write off 100 percent of their health care costs as a tax deduction</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''A Senseless Health Deduction'' (editorial, Oct. 14):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''A Senseless Health Deduction'' (editorial, Oct. 14):</p>
        <p>The Congressional Republicans' A-Plus Health Care Deduction would allow America's 43 million uninsured to write off 100 percent of their health care costs. It's the same tax break already provided to Fortune 500 companies, big labor unions and the self-employed.</p>
        <p>Even the Treasury Department admits that our proposal will reduce the number of uninsured by at least 600,000, and the bipartisan Joint Committee on Taxation says a full tax deduction would help 26 million Americans better afford health care.</p>
        <p>Low-  and middle-income Americans will benefit most; according to the nonpartisan General Accounting Office, at least 21 million people in the 15 percent tax bracket and another 5 million in the 28 percent bracket will benefit. Under our plan, the newly insured would number 1.6 million, compared with only 45,000 under the Democrats' tax credit.</p>
        <p>J. DENNIS HASTERT  Speaker of the House  Washington, Oct. 17, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
